I recommend you to go through the contracts and look at the `claim_points` function and see what it demands For eg. in ex 3 -

let (current_counter_value) = user_counters_storage.read(sender_address)

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
Yes good catch!
I have updated the contracts to make full use of acounts contracts and argent X. This means that for every transaction, your tx has to go through an account contract; these usually have a nonce. This nonce is ifferent at every tx, and so you'll never get the same hash twice.
Salt was used before in order to achieve that; it is not necessary anymore. Does that make sense?

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
From what i am reading, you are new to smart contracts - and this is fine!
The program "lives" in the network, starknet. In starknet, there is both the code (deployed) and the storage variables.
You get to interact with the contract throuh voyager. So you can read the code on Github; understand what is required; and on voyager, you can call the desired functions through their website. The call is then sent to the network and executed, and the variables are updated

Author: Henri#6408
Content:
When you click on "transact", you are sending a transaction.
You should check the status of your transaction to mlake sure it is executed. Please check this https://github.com/l-henri/starknet-cairo-101#transaction-status
What happens most likely is that you are sending two transactions in a row; and one of them is not executed properly, because of a nonce issue in Argent X.
If you try again now, the transaction will go through and you'll be able to increment your counter

Author: odinfree
Content:
Hello Fren 

It's really great to have you on board. Cairo is not that hard to learn and a promising skill in your toolbox. This tutorial will show you how to write and implement a StarkNet contract: 

https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/index.html 

and https://starknet.io/recorded-tutorials/ 

Cairo was specifically designed to be efficient within STARK, which is the cryptography that Starknet uses to make computations cheap. You can read more about Cairo here: https://www.cairo-lang.org/ and https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/


Have a nice day Oli

Author: kamadd
Content:
Can anyone tell me why I got this error? 
```
func main():
  [ap] = 3; ap++
  assert [ap] = [ap-1] * [ap-1] * [ap-1]
  ret
end
```
```
Got an error:
demo.cairo:4:5: Error at pc=0:3:
An ASSERT_EQ instruction failed: 9 != 27.
    assert [ap] = [ap-1] * [ap-1] * [ap-1]
    ^************************************^
Error: Run must be ended before calling read_return_values.
```

Author: kamadd
Content: I thought expression  is recursively defined: if `x*x` is an expression, `x*x*x` should also be expression, where x is an expression.

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: The Cairo instruction that substitutes something into ap also takes care to advance ap (when you're reading sourcecode and not Cairo bytecode, it's more convenient to see this explicitly)

Author: kamadd
Content: So, ap++ is like a comment?

Author: FeedTheFed | StarkWare#8826
Content: I wouldn't say that, the point is to treat "[ap]=3;ap++" as a single instruction

Author: kamadd
Content: But, â€œ[ap] = 3â€ only also advances ap?

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content: [ap] = 3 does not advance ap.

Author: kamadd
Content: Yeah, I just tested.

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content:
assert [ap] = [ap-1] * [ap-1] * [ap-1]
mixes high level (assert) syntax, with low level register access (ap).
Using ap directly in compound expressions is not well defined.

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content: We will probably fix it at some point but currently, it is not a priority for us.

Author: kamadd
Content:
Thanks you!
I asked this question because I'm trying to solve polynomial exercise in 5 instructions. https://starknet.io/docs/how_cairo_works/cairo_intro.html#a-simple-cairo-program-exercise
code below won't work.
```
func main():
    [ap] = 100; ap++

    let x = [ap-1]
    let x1 = x * 45
    let x2 = 23 * x * x
    let x3 = x * x * x
    assert [ap] = x3 + x2 + x1 + 67

    ret
end
```
This is an error I got.
```
An ASSERT_EQ instruction failed: 10000 != 1234567.
    assert [ap] = x3 + x2 + x1 + 67
    ^*****************************^
```
Maybe, `let` doesn't increment `ap`?

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content: let only gives a name to an expression it does not generate opcodes on its own so definitely does not increase ap.

Author: kamadd
Content: So, I need to count `ap` implicitly increated by `assert` instruction? like,  `assert [ap+8] = x3 + x2 + x1 + 67` worked.

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content:
you can use
tempvar res =  x3 + x2 + x1 + 67

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content:
or you could add a return value to main
func main() -> (res):
    [ap] = 100; ap++

    let x = [ap-1]
    let x1 = x * 45
    let x2 = 23 * x * x
    let x3 = x * x * x

    return (res =  x3 + x2 + x1 + 67)
end

Author: ilya.lesokhin
Content:
Maybe not well defined wasn't the best way of phrasing it.
The generated code is deterministic.

but assert [ap] = [ap-1] * [ap-1] * [ap-1]
Asks the compiler  to assign a value to [ap] and the compiler also uses [ap] as temporary storage for the computation of the  [ap-1] * [ap-1] * [ap-1] compound expression.
So you get an error.

Author: kamadd
Content:
Thanks!
I made a small experiment. Let's have the following setting.  
```
[ap] = 100; ap++

[ap] = 1; ap++
[ap] = 2; ap++
[ap] = 3; ap++
```
Then, 
`assert [ap] = [ap-1] + [ap-2] + [ap-3]` will store `5` in `ap` .
`assert [ap] = [ap-3] + [ap-2] + [ap-1]` will store `3` in `ap` .
It seems the evaluation of expression is done backward

Author: kamadd
Content: And each evaluation doesn't advance `ap`

Author: kamadd
Content: But, it seems that if the expression is defined by `let`, the direction of evaluation is forwardðŸ˜…

Author: odinfree
Content:
Hello fren

the team is working on full decentralization, but not from day one.

You can not run a StarkNet full node yet. We're currently developing the Constellations phase of StarkNet (see the planned roadmap here: https://medium.com/starkware/on-the-road-to-starknet-a-permissionless-stark-powered-l2-zk-rollup-83be53640880). In this phase we have one sequencer. A full node is currently being developed (but note that it's not a sequencer, it just follows the state of the network rather than adding to it). In the Universe phase, we'll finally move to the multiple-sequencers mode and then you (that is, anyone  ) will be able to fully participate in running the network.

You can also read more about the decentralization plan and roadmap here: 

https://discordapp.com/channels/793094838509764618/853954510515208192/917098926337843251

And this fantastic thread by Louis: 
https://twitter.com/GuthL/status/1463180474914951177

Have a great day

Oli

Author: _trevis_
Content:
`user_values_storage` associates an `account` and  a `slot` to a `value`  ( See #29: `user_values_storage(account: felt, slot: felt) -> (user_values_storage: felt):`)
So its more a (key1, key2) --> value pairing. (like row and column of a 2d table/matrix).
When reading it you call `.read(key1, key2)` to get `value`; when you write, you call `.write(key1, key2, value)`

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
```py
func get_sum_internal{ range_check_ptr}(length : felt, array : felt*) -> (sum : felt):
```
array is a pointer as you can see and this syntax [array] allows you to access the values which array points to

Author: lucasstarkware

to access the next value of the array you'll have to increment the pointer 
```py
let (current_sum) = get_sum_internal(length=length - 1, array=array + 1)
```
which is done at the function call

Content:
Bonjour les amis !

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: `base_token_uri` is the part of the metadata uri that's common to all of your nfts for example if you store the metadata on IPFS your `base_token_uri` could be `https://ipfs.io/ipfs/`, the `base_token_uri_len` would be 21 and then the `token_uri_suffix` would be the CID of your metadata so something like `QmRPwZS....`

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
for now cairo only handles felts which are integers so if you want to pass any argument it has to be ints to convert a short string to int you can use `int.from_bytes("YOUR STRING".encode(), byteorder="big")` and for hex you can use `int("YOUR HEX", 16)`. If you want to deploy the contract on testnet you'll also have to specify `--network goerli` so your final command should look like that 
```bash
nile deploy ERC721 123... 123... 123... --network goerli
```

from starkware.cairo.common.dict_access import DictAccess

Author: Chauncee#8602
Content:
func build_dict{output_ptr : felt*}(
        key_list : felt*, value_list : felt*, n_steps,
        dict : DictAccess*) -> (dict : DictAccess*):
    if n_steps == 0:
        return (dict=dict)
    end

    # Set the key 
    assert dict.key = [key_list]
    # Set the previous value
    assert dict.prev_value = [value_list]
    # Set the new value
    assert dict.new_value = [value_list + 1]
    serialize_word(dict.new_value)
    # Call build_dict recursively.
    return build_dict(
        key_list=key_list + 1,
        value_list=value_list + 2,
        n_steps=n_steps - 1,
        dict=dict + DictAccess.SIZE)
end

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
lets say that felts' max value is a 10 and that a uint256 can go up to 15.
If you want to create a uint256 that's 13 you'd have to do
Uint256(10, 3) because 13 is 10 (max felt value) + 3
If you want to create a uint256 that's 7 you'd have to do
Uint256(7, 0) because 7 is 7 + 0

Author: jpick713
Content: It would always choose this pattern right, never would do uint256(7,6) right?

Author: jpick713
Content: basically if the second argument is non-zero it would enforce that first arg is max_felt?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
```py
# Represents an integer in the range [0, 2^256).
struct Uint256:
    # The low 128 bits of the value.
    member low : felt
    # The high 128 bits of the value.
    member high : felt
end
```

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: this is the official code so the first one should be up to 2^128

Author: kaboosan
Content:
Hi,  on the documentation (https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/how_cairo_works/consts.html) it is mention that ap may not be able to compute change of ap. In general you should not put more than 1 operator when you deal  with ap. In your case I did something like this:

`%builtins output
from starkware.cairo.common.serialize import serialize_word

func main{output_ptr : felt*}():

    let c1 = ap
    [c1] = 23; ap++
    let c2 = ap
    [c2] = 45; ap++
    let c3 = ap
    [c3] = 67; ap++
    
    [ap] = 100; ap++
    
    [ap] = [ap - 1] * [ap - 1]; ap++
    [ap] = [ap - 2] * [ap - 1]; ap++
    
    let exp1 = ap
    [exp1] = [c1] * [ap - 2]; ap++
    [ap] = [ap - 2] + [exp1]; ap++ 
    
    let exp2 = ap
    [exp2] = [c2] * [ap - 5]; ap++
    [ap] = [ap - 2] + [exp2]; ap++ 
    
    [ap] = [ap - 1] + [c3]; ap++
    
    serialize_word([ap - 1])
    return ()
end`

Author: _dsi
Content: Okkk, I came to the conclusion that I couldn't put more than one calculation but without understanding why

Author: _dsi
Content: Thank you, I get it now

Author: _dsi
Content:
There is just something I find weird is that 
```
[ap] = 23 * [ap - 1] # doesn't work : Error: Expected a dereference expression.
[ap] = [ap - 1] * 23 # work 
```
Do you know why ?

Author: kaboosan
Content: I'm really not an expert of Cairo but my understanding is that in your first case the compiler is not able to track the change of ap because of instruction "23" between ap and ap-1.  So the compiler will jump in memory to get 23 and lose reference of ap. In your second line I assume that  23 is the last element to compute so he do not need to track [ap -1]. Of course this is a tricky part and expert should confirm.

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
not sure to understand what you mean. From my understanding you have a list of `(key: felt, value: felt)` and you need to compute the cumulative sum of the values from the same key so if you have a list that looks like that `[(1, 2), (2, 3), (1, 4), (1, 9), (2, 4)]` you'd have a dict before squashing that would look like that:
```md
| KEY  | PREV | NEXT |
| :--: | :--: | :--: |
| 1    | 2    | 6    |
| 1    | 6    | 15   |
| 2    | 3    | 7    |
```
then you'd have to squash it to obtain:
```md
| KEY  | PREV | NEXT |
| :--: | :--: | :--: |
| 1    | 2    | 15   |
| 2    | 3    | 7    |
```
So you'd have only one dict that contains the cumulative sum of the key-value pairs

Author: protoplanetary
Content:
Hi folks! Just getting started with Cairo and StarkNet here, and I'm following the documentation at https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/quickstart.html

I'm on a fresh install of Ubuntu, and there seem to have been some steps that were just assumed and were missing from the documentation that I had to figure out myself. It might save newcomers some time if these were in the documentation!

1. Prior to the first step, install the following (all needed, and note 3.9 is latest Python but I'm using 3.7 for consistency):

sudo apt install -y python3.7 python3.7-venv python3.7-dev libgmp3-dev gcc

Note that libgmp3-dev was mentioned in the docs but not any of the others. I put it all in one line.

2. Once you're inside the Python venv, you need to install the 'wheel' package prior to the other three (also not mentioned in the docs):

pip3 install **wheel** ecdsa fastecdsa sympy

These two changes to the quickstart page would likely save newbs like me at least 20 minutes of head scratching! Just suggestions ðŸ™‚ 

P.S. here are the salient errors I fixed with the above, in case anyone is searching for them here in Discord ðŸ™‚ 

* The virtual environment was not created successfully because ensurepip is not
available.
* error: invalid command 'bdist_wheel'
* ERROR: Failed building wheel for fastecdsa
* error: command 'x86_64-linux-gnu-gcc' failed: No such file or directory

Author: odinfree
Content:
Hello Fren 

It's really great to have you on board. Cairo is not that hard to learn and a promising skill in your toolbox. I can list you some tutorials and open-source resources: 

https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/hello_starknet/index.html 

and https://starknet.io/recorded-tutorials/ 

Henri's new tutorial:
https://github.com/l-henri/starknet-cairo-101
and
https://github.com/l-henri/starknet-erc721

and 

https://symbonstark.surge.sh/#/

Cairo was specifically designed to be efficient within STARK, which is the cryptography that Starknet uses to make computations cheap. You can read more about Cairo here: https://www.cairo-lang.org/ and https://www.cairo-lang.org/docs/

When you master Cairo, come to our discord to the channel community-jobs, write a short summary of your skills and we will hook you up. 

https://discord.com/channels/793094838509764618/898210860030386178

Have a nice day

Content: what means  Uint256 = Uint256(1,0) ?

Author: wind.rider
Content: Hi,alpha_tornado, can you describe your question in more detail?ðŸ˜€

Author: gaetbout
Content:
a felt is encoded en 252 bits, and sometimes you need to deal with (potentially) bigger numbers so you create a Uint encoded on 256 bits.
By default in cairo 1, 2, 3, 42, 69 are  felt . 
Uint256(1,0)  will create a number on 256 bits that is 1
It is encoded in 2 parts  (low and high) 128 bits each
for more info check: https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo-lang/blob/master/src/starkware/cairo/common/uint256.cairo

Author: martinkrug
Content: You can't reassign a variable in Cairo. Just can do 'assert [array + n] = val_n' and if the n position in array is assigned it will check the value and if it's not, it will assign the value... memory in Cairo is not dynamic, variables are immutable

Author: rootulp
Content:
Any tips on how to resolve `Actual fee exceeded max fee.` ? https://alpha4.starknet.io/feeder_gateway/get_transaction_receipt?transactionHash=0x2beb54e1ff07510c4da2eb7b331180a4a7e842d16269df44d9ccf656d7623b7

Author: rootulp
Content: I was able to resolve this. If you encounter `"Actual fee exceeded max fee.\n11399742106500 > 11057749843305"`  then re-submit the transaction but in the Argent X transaction screen, manually edit the "Network fee" to be larger than the higher number in the error

```
@constructor
func constructor{syscall_ptr : felt*, pedersen_ptr : HashBuiltin*, range_check_ptr}(

```
# Represents an integer in the range [0, 2^256).
struct Uint256:
    # The low 128 bits of the value.
    member low : felt
    # The high 128 bits of the value.
    member high : felt
end

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
the 2 values that you have to supply should satisfy all the asserts here:
```py
assert_not_zero(value_a)
assert_nn(value_b)
assert_not_equal(value_a, value_b)
assert_le(value_a, 75)
assert_in_range(value_a, 40, 70)
assert_lt(value_b, 1)
```
so a != 0, b >= 0 ....

Author: salsasteve
Content: can someone explain ```let (var1)``` and ```let var2``` syntax?

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
`let (var1)` is for function returns (functions only return tuples for now so you have to unpack them for example `let (var1) = get_contract_address()`
`let var2` is for the rest, for example `let var2 = 1 + 2`

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: Ok so it's because you check the balance of the caller of your contract but `faucet` credits the contract that calls the function, in your case it's your contract. If you want the user to have the tokens you'd have to transfer them from your contract to the caller after calling `faucet`

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
```py
let (after_balance: Uint256) = IDTKERC20.balanceOf(
        contract_address=erc20_token_address,
        account=caller_address
    )
```
here you check the balance of the caller but the caller has no token because he didn't call faucet it's your smart-contract that called faucet

you should probably add events to monitor what's happening in your contract but i think it doesn't work because every amount is 0.

`let (caller_has_enough: felt) = uint256_le(amount, balance_of_caller)`
`assert caller_has_enough = 1`
this passes because you use `uint256_le` and 0 <= 0
The allowance check passes because you want to move 0 token

Author: whatthedev
Content:
FYI in Cairo Playground challenge Bitwise Operations, this original return statement

`return bitwise_xor(digit0, digit1)`

results in an error, and so needs to be replaced with

`    let (res) = bitwise_xor(digit0, digit1)
    return (res)`

This is maybe due to Cairo v.0.9.0 changing function's return type from a struct to a named tuple.

Author: cryptoleek.
Content: well done mate. i finished all the tutorials which is a lot of fun. i am here to help if you stuck

Author: cryptoleek.
Content: in cairo or blockchain general there is no string concept, everything is a felt or hex,

Author: cryptoleek.
Content: so you need to translate your string to decimal or hex decimal

Author: cryptoleek.
Content: the website i am using to translate this is https://www.rapidtables.com/convert/number/decimal-to-hex.html

Author: cryptoleek.
Content: or you can use helper functions to help you

Author: lucasstarkware
Content:
`let (var) = foo()`
This is because functions only return tuples so you have to unpack the tuple
`let var = (something)` 
is to create a tuple with `something` in it
`let (var) = (something)` has no effect on anything because you create a tuple that you instantly unpack

It seems that the compilator is too permissive for call of functions of external contract...ðŸ˜¢

Author: alex_b1
lucasstarkware
Content:
you're not charging anything to register someone as a breeder that's the problem. You say that the price is `registration_price` but you never charge it. You'd need to add:
```py
let (self_address) = get_contract_address()
IERC20.transferFrom(contract_address=dummy_token_address, sender=evaluator_address, recipient=self_address, amount=Uint256(registration_price, 0))
```

Author: lucasstarkware
Content: (something like this make sure that it's the right thing) but basically the evaluator checks that you indeed charged him for his registration which is just transferring some of his dummy tokens to yourself and it also checks that this amount is the one that you return in your `registration_price` view

Author: barretodavid
Content: how do I turn a `felt` into a `uint256` if I don't know the value in advance? I'm aware of the `Uint256` struct from the library from `starkware.cairo.common.uint256` but it seems like you need to know if it is a small or a big value to properly use the `low` and `high` members of the struct

Author: barretodavid
Content:
I'm in particular stuck at exercise 4 of the erc721 workshop. The Evaluator calls:
```
IExerciseSolution.token_of_owner_by_index(
    contract_address=submited_exercise_address,   
    account=evaluator_address,
    index=0
)
```
and according to the provided interface, `index` is of type `felt` not `Uint256`
```
@contract_interface
namespace IExerciseSolution:
    ...
    func token_of_owner_by_index(account : felt, index : felt) -> (token_id : Uint256):
    end
    ....
end
```
but when I receive the value I want to make sure that it is smaller than the value returned by `balanceOf` that it's a `Uint256` according to OZ implementation of ERC721

Author: barretodavid
Content: but that would be comparing a `Uint256` against a `felt` which seems odd

Author: jpick713
Content: if it is not big, then highest 128 bits should just be 0, does that throw off your code in any way?

Author: barretodavid
Content: well, from the code I see that the value passed is exactly 0 but I wanted to generalize the operation. What if another contract tries to pass an index that is bigger then 2^128?

Author: barretodavid
Content: how do I use the struct to create a Uint256 that represents the number `(2^128)+1` for example?

Author: jpick713
Content: the first 128 bits (1) are in the low and the next 128 bits (looks like also 1) go in the high

Author: barretodavid
Content: so `(2^128)+1` would be created like `Uint256(1,1)`?

Author: barretodavid
Content:
for context this is what the library does:
```
# Represents an integer in the range [0, 2^256).
struct Uint256:
    # The low 128 bits of the value.
    member low : felt
    # The high 128 bits of the value.
    member high : felt
end
```

Author: jpick713
Content: high is shifted 128 bits ðŸ‘

Author: jpick713
Content: Uint256(1,1) would be equivalent to 1*2^128 + 1

Author: barretodavid
Content: ok I'll try that, thanks

Author: whatthedev
Content: In `func set_user_values` you need to pass an array (i.e., enter the values of an array in the correct order, separated by commas) which is then passed to `func set_user_values_internal` which fills the array in memory. Take a close look at that second function to see how it recursively fills the array.  If you need more help with arrays, challenge "dynamic allocation" in https://www.cairo-lang.org/playground/ might help. If you need more help with recursion, try "recursion" challenge there. Hope that helps! ðŸ—ï¸

Author: marciob
Content: I'm studying the ex08 from Cairo 101, I was able to pass but I didn't understand well the recursion function, could anyone clarify?

Author: marciob
Content:
some dumb questions about that:

1. at line 99 it says that when `length = 0` it starts summing, but I donâ€™t see any sum `within if(length == 0)` statement, as it also is referring at line 101

2. at line 106 Iâ€™d like to better know what `array=array + 1` is doing, trying to know how it makes sense in the logic

3. also at line 109, itâ€™s previously said that line is reached only when `length=0`, if thatâ€™s the case then `length - 1` would be -1 at that time, how it makes sense to pass -1 as length to save into `user_values_storage`?

Author: scarletssstarktitan
Content: i have answered you in #ðŸ¼ï½œgeneral-chat  pls have a check ,thanks for your supporting

Author: sefasercan
Content: Thank you

Author: whatthedev
Content:
1. When `length = 0`, this initiates the first `return ()` from the call on line 106. Upon return, we're back to `length = 1`. And then we proceed to line 109 for the first time to begin to fill the array. 

3. The comment on line 108 would better read `# This part of the function is first reached AFTER RETURN FROM length=0.` (because now we are back to `length = 1`)

2. I think you mean line 106. To see the logic, suppose for example that when `func set_user_values_internal` is called in line 85, we begin with `length` = 5 and `array` = 0 (a pointer to the first storage address of `array`)--just making up two numbers to use. The first time we reach line 106, this call reduces `length` to 4 and increases `array` to 1. 

Then we keep hitting line 106 until `length` has been reduced to 0, and `array` has been increased to 5. This initiates the first return (answer 1 above). Upon this first return, the values are back to `length` = 1, and `array` = 4 (which is the pointer to the last storage address of `array`). So, the first time line 109 is reached it is: `user_values_storage.write(account, 0, [4])`. This stores the last member of `array` (`[4]`) in slot 0 of  `user_value_storage`.

Then the next return (again from call at line 106) gets us to `length` = 2 and `array` = 3. So the next write on line 109 stores the next-to-last member of `array` (`[3]`) in slot 1.

And so on, until the final write stores the first member of `array` (`[0]`) in slot 4. Hope that helps!

0x05c6b1379f1d4c8a4f5db781a706b63a885f3f9570f7863629e99e2342ac344c

Anyways, I think I'm out of ways to migrate my points and will just have to take the L. If there's still another way, a sneaky way, that I just need to find... let me know please.

Hello,
Same issue from my side. 
It seems the ex10 contract was not deployed with the right erc20. 
From Tx : 0x06ba31f07560c61646aef5d9b07252a2d1c148f57ea6492c70d096923a6d91a7
```
constructor_calldata    felt*    

[
  "0x3a4cfde2be18b3d49cf56b60910f8a9f2fb35528a6bae0a3d039d8a2421b1cf",
  "0xad0cae6669edbf0aa57a37dbea0566f4e11f131bf4be8cc2efdfcb27b6d0ba",
  "1",
  "a"
]
```
The used ERC20 is the first element while the one from the exercice should be 0x044f65adbdb59bf1db71e8b69efb7c9d0b810db94c1730a05fa5751b02d396de

Author: 0xkubi.stark
Content:
Hello Starkfrens, any chance someone can help me, please?
I'm currently trying to follow the replay from the last Basecamp session (about tests in Cairo1 - link here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6f1u1vMNNh0&t=1900s) but I get an error message when trying to run the very first test... ðŸ˜¢

Please allow me to describe you the context and my issue:

Author: 0xkubi.stark
Content:
1) I have initialized my project using Scarb.
2) I have created an `ERC20.cairo` file in the `src/` folder.
3) In `ERC20.cairo`, I have copied/pasted the content from Starkware's ERC20 implementation example (https://github.com/starkware-libs/cairo/blob/main/crates/cairo-lang-starknet/test_data/erc20.cairo).
4) I added a `tests` module, including a `test_constructor` function, exactly like Robert did (see here for his function: https://www.youtube.com/live/6f1u1vMNNh0?feature=share&t=3207).
5) I added: `mod ERC20;` in `lib.cairo`.
6) I created and implemented the `cairo_project_toml file`, just like Robert does in the replay from live coding session.

Now, when I run: `cairo-test --starknet .` (which is the exact same command that Robert runs in his terminal) I get the following error message:
```
error: Plugin diagnostic: Method `is_zero` not found on type "core::starknet::contract_address::ContractAddress". Did you import the correct trait and impl?
 --> ERC20.cairo:34:27
        assert(!recipient.is_zero(), 'ERC20: mint to the 0 address');
                          ^*****^

error: Plugin diagnostic: Method `is_zero` not found on type "core::starknet::contract_address::ContractAddress". Did you import the correct trait and impl?
 --> ERC20.cairo:102:24
        assert(!sender.is_zero(), 'ERC20: transfer from 0');
                       ^*****^

error: Plugin diagnostic: Method `is_zero` not found on type "core::starknet::contract_address::ContractAddress". Did you import the correct trait and impl?
 --> ERC20.cairo:103:27
        assert(!recipient.is_zero(), 'ERC20: transfer to 0');
                          ^*****^

error: Plugin diagnostic: Method `is_zero` not found on type "core::starknet::contract_address::ContractAddress". Did you import the correct trait and impl?
 --> ERC20.cairo:120:25
        assert(!spender.is_zero(), 'ERC20: approve from 0');
                        ^*****^

Error: failed to compile: .
```

Author: 0xkubi.stark
Content:
The thing is, that at that point, Robert test is passing without error but mine does not!
Unfortunately, I don't understand how come I get this: "Method is_zero not found" error when I'm copy/pasting the official ERC20 contract template from Starkware and implementing the same test than Robert... 
I do assume the error obviously comes from me but I tried several times and always end up with the same error...
I can't see what I'm doing wrong here...  Would anyone be so kind to give me some help, please?

(here's my repo if you wanna take a look at my code ->  https://github.com/0xKubitus/cairo1-tests-workshop/tree/following-basecamp-session4-replay)


P.S: Running `scarb --version` in my terminal returns:
```
scarb 0.2.0-alpha.0 (04eb95172 2023-04-13)
cairo: 1.0.0-alpha.7
```
(So I should have the requested environment for the workshop)



Many thanks in advance for your help, fellow Stark-troopers ðŸ«¶

Author: 0xkubi.stark
Content:
Hi @robert I hope you don't mind me pinging you here...
If by any chance you could have a moment to spare to help me figure why I'm getting this error, it would be much appreciated ðŸ™

Author: robertkodra
Content:
Ah, just saw the ping. Replying here as well:

depending on which cairo version you are, the library moved to 
```rust
use starknet::contract_address::ContractAddressZeroable;
```

You'll need to import this in the ERC20. Let me know if it works.

Author: 0xkubi.stark
Content: Thanks very much for having taken the time to reply, it was indeed what's was missing in the ERC20 contract!
